To encumber with a handicap in any contest; hence, in general,to place at disadvantage; as, the candidate was heavily handicapped.

Disposition to please or oblige; obliging compliance with thewishes of others; a deportment indicative of a desire to please;courtesy; civility.These [ladies] . . . are by the just complaisance and gallantry ofour nation the most powerful part of our people. Addison.They strive with their own hearts and keep them down, In complaisanceto all the fools in town. Young.

One who understands, or knows by experience. [R.] Dryden.
In a dioecious manner. Dioeciously hermaphrodite (Bot.), havingflowers structurally perfect, but practically dioecious, -- those onone plant producing no pollen, and those on another no ovules.
A minute particular; a small or minor detail; -- used chieflyin the plural.
